  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v0 is a set and v1 is a set and (it is wrong that (v0 is empty) and it is wrong that (v1 is empty)) then (\SETcard{ v0 } \ORDless \SETcard{ v1 } iff ((for some v2, (v2 is a map from v0 to v1 and v2 is injective)) and it is wrong that (for some v2, (v2 is a surjective map from v0 to v1))))))
Proof:
  ((for some v0, (v0 is a map from x to y and v0 is injective)) and it is wrong that (for some v0, (v0 is a surjective map from x to y))) iff (\SETcard{ x } \ORDleq \SETcard{ y } and it is wrong that (\SETcard{ y } \ORDleq \SETcard{ x }))
  (\SETcard{ x } \ORDleq \SETcard{ y } and it is wrong that (\SETcard{ y } \ORDleq \SETcard{ x })) iff (\SETcard{ x } \ORDleq \SETcard{ y } and it is wrong that (\SETcard{ x } is equal to \SETcard{ y }))
  (\SETcard{ x } \ORDleq \SETcard{ y } and it is wrong that (\SETcard{ x } is equal to \SETcard{ y })) iff \SETcard{ x } \ORDless \SETcard{ y }
Qed.

Theorem (cardinality_of_image):
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (for all v3, (if v2 is a set and v3 is a set and v1 is a map from v2 to v3 and v0 is a subclass of v2 then \SETcard{ \FUNim{ v1 }{ v0 } } \ORDleq \SETcard{ v0 }))))
Proof:
  if a is empty then the thesis holds
  if it is wrong that (a is empty) then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    f \FUNrest a is a surjective map from a to \FUNim{ f }{ a }
    it is wrong that (\FUNim{ f }{ a } is empty)
    \SETcard{ \FUNim{ f }{ a } } \ORDleq \SETcard{ a }
    Proof:
      a is a set and \FUNim{ f }{ a } is a set
    Qed.
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem (Cantor_I):
  for all v0, (if v0 is a set then it is wrong that (for some v1, (v1 is a surjective map from v0 to \SETpow( v0 ))))
Proof:
  it is wrong that (the thesis holds)
  f is a surjective map from x to \SETpow( x )
  C is a class and (if x is a set then C is a set) and for all v0, (v0 is an element of C iff (v0 is an element of x and v0 is an object and it is wrong that (v0 is an element of the value of f under v0)))
  C is an element of \SETpow( x )
  u is an element of x and the value of f under u is equal to C
  u is an element of C iff (u is an element of the value of f under u iff it is wrong that (u is an element of C))
  falsity holds
Qed.

Theorem (Cantor_II):
  for all v0, (if v0 is a set then \SETcard{ v0 } \ORDless \SETcard{ \SETpow( v0 ) })
Proof:
  if x is empty then the thesis holds
  if it is wrong that (x is empty) then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    it is wrong that (the thesis holds)
    \SETcard{ \SETpow( x ) } \ORDleq \SETcard{ x }
    for some v0, (v0 is a surjective map from x to \SETpow( x ))
    Proof:
      \SETpow( x ) is a set and it is wrong that (\SETpow( x ) is empty)
    Qed.
    falsity holds
  Qed.
Qed.

Definition:
  for all v0, ((v0 is equal to \Card) iff (v0 is a class and for all v1, (v1 is an element of v0 iff (v1 is a cardinal number and v1 is infinite and v1 is an object))))

Theorem:
  for all v0, (if v0 is an ordinal number and v0 is infinite then \SETcard{ \ORDsucc( v0 ) } is equal to \SETcard{ v0 })
Proof:
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \ORDsucc( \alpha ) then (v0 \ORDless \ORDomega or (\ORDomega \ORDleq v0 and v0 \ORDless \alpha) or v0 is equal to \alpha))
  f is a map and (the domain of f is equal to \ORDsucc( \alpha )) and for all v0, (if v0 is an object then (if v0 is an element of the domain of f then ((if v0 \ORDless \ORDomega then (the value of f under v0 is equal to \ORDsucc( v0 ))) and (if \ORDomega \ORDleq v0 and v0 \ORDless \alpha then (the value of f under v0 is equal to v0)) and (if v0 is equal to \alpha then (the value of f under v0 is equal to \SETempty)))))
  f is a map from \ORDsucc( \alpha ) to \alpha
  Proof:
    for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \ORDsucc( \alpha ) then the value of f under v0 is an element of \alpha)
    Proof:
      \beta is an element of \ORDsucc( \alpha )
      if \beta \ORDless \ORDomega then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        the value of f under \beta is equal to \ORDsucc( \beta ) and \ORDsucc( \beta ) \ORDless \ORDomega and \ORDomega \ORDleq \alpha
      Qed.
      if \ORDomega \ORDleq \beta and \beta \ORDless \alpha then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        the value of f under \beta is equal to \beta and \beta \ORDless \alpha
      Qed.
      if \beta is equal to \alpha then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        the value of f under \beta is equal to \SETempty and \SETempty \ORDless \alpha
      Qed.
    Qed.
  Qed.
  f is surjective onto \alpha
  Proof:
    for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \alpha then for some v1, (v1 is an element of \ORDsucc( \alpha ) and v0 is equal to the value of f under v1))
    Proof:
      \beta is an element of \alpha
      \beta is equal to \SETempty or (\SETempty \ORDless \beta and \beta \ORDless \ORDomega) or \ORDomega \ORDleq \beta
      if \beta is equal to \SETempty then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        \beta is equal to the value of f under \alpha
      Qed.
      if \SETempty \ORDless \beta and \beta \ORDless \ORDomega then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        \beta' is an ordinal number and \beta is equal to \ORDsucc( \beta' )
        \beta' \ORDless \ORDomega
        \beta is equal to the value of f under \beta'
      Qed.
      if \ORDomega \ORDleq \beta then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        \beta is equal to the value of f under \beta
      Qed.
    Qed.
  Qed.
  f is injective
  Proof:
    for all v0, (for all v1, (if v0 is an element of \ORDsucc( \alpha ) and v1 is an element of \ORDsucc( \alpha ) then (if it is wrong that (v0 is equal to v1) then it is wrong that (the value of f under v0 is equal to the value of f under v1))))
    Proof:
      \beta is an element of \ORDsucc( \alpha ) and \gamma is an element of \ORDsucc( \alpha )
      it is wrong that (\beta is equal to \gamma)
      if \beta \ORDless \ORDomega then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        if \gamma is equal to \alpha then (the value of f under \beta is equal to \ORDsucc( \beta ) and it is wrong that (\ORDsucc( \beta ) is equal to \SETempty) and \SETempty is equal to the value of f under \gamma)
        if \ORDomega \ORDleq \gamma and \gamma \ORDless \alpha then (the value of f under \beta is equal to \ORDsucc( \beta ) and \ORDsucc( \beta ) \ORDless \ORDomega and \ORDomega \ORDleq \gamma and \gamma is equal to the value of f under \gamma)
      Qed.
      if \ORDomega \ORDleq \beta and \beta \ORDless \alpha then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        if \gamma is equal to \alpha then (the value of f under \beta is equal to \beta and \ORDomega \ORDleq \beta and \SETempty \ORDless \ORDomega and \SETempty is equal to the value of f under \gamma)
        if \gamma \ORDless \ORDomega then (the value of f under \beta is equal to \beta and \ORDomega \ORDleq \beta and \ORDsucc( \gamma ) \ORDless \ORDomega and \ORDsucc( \gamma ) is equal to the value of f under \gamma)
      Qed.
      if \beta is equal to \alpha then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        if \gamma \ORDless \ORDomega then (the value of f under \beta is equal to \SETempty and it is wrong that (\SETempty is equal to \ORDsucc( \gamma )) and \ORDsucc( \gamma ) is equal to the value of f under \gamma)
        if \ORDomega \ORDleq \gamma and \gamma \ORDless \alpha then (the value of f under \beta is equal to \SETempty and \SETempty \ORDless \ORDomega and \ORDomega \ORDleq \gamma and \gamma is equal to the value of f under \gamma)
      Qed.
    Qed.
  Qed.
  f is a bijection between \ORDsucc( \alpha ) and \alpha
  \ORDsucc( \alpha ) is equinumerous to \alpha
  \SETcard{ \ORDsucc( \alpha ) } is equal to \SETcard{ \alpha }
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (if v0 is a cardinal number and v0 is infinite then v0 is a limit ordinal)
Proof:
  \kappa is a cardinal number and \kappa is infinite
  it is wrong that (\kappa is a limit ordinal)
  it is wrong that (\kappa is equal to \SETempty)
  \kappa is a successor ordinal
  Proof:
    \kappa is an ordinal number
  Qed.
  \alpha is an ordinal number and \kappa is equal to \ORDsucc( \alpha )
  \kappa \ORDless \alpha and \ORDomega \ORDleq \kappa
  \SETcard{ \ORDsucc( \alpha ) } is equal to \SETcard{ \alpha }
  \alpha \ORDless \SETcard{ \kappa } and \kappa is equinumerous to \kappa
  falsity holds
Qed.

Theorem (Burali_Forti_Paradox):
  it is wrong that (\Ord is a set)
Proof:
  it is wrong that (the thesis holds)
  \Ord is transitive and for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \Ord then v0 is transitive)
  \Ord is an ordinal number
  \Ord is an element of \Ord
  falsity holds
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (if v0 is an ordinal number then for some v1, (v1 is a cardinal number and v0 \ORDless v1))
Proof:
  \alpha is an ordinal number
  \kappa is equal to \SETcard{ \SETpow( \alpha ) }
  \SETcard{ \alpha } \ORDless \kappa
  \alpha \ORDless \kappa
  Proof:
    it is wrong that (the thesis holds)
    \SETcard{ \SETpow( \alpha ) } is equal to \kappa and \kappa \ORDleq \alpha
    \kappa is equal to \SETcard{ \SETpow( \alpha ) } and \SETcard{ \SETpow( \alpha ) } is equal to \SETcard{ \SETcard{ \SETpow( \alpha ) } } and \SETcard{ \SETcard{ \SETpow( \alpha ) } } \ORDleq \SETcard{ \alpha }
    falsity holds
  Qed.
Qed.

Definition:
  for all v0, (if v0 is a cardinal number then for all v1, ((v1 is equal to \CARDsucc{ v0 }) iff (v1 is a cardinal number and v0 \ORDless v1 and it is wrong that (for some v2, (v2 is a cardinal number and v0 \ORDless v2 and v2 \ORDless v1)))))

Definition:
  for all v0, ((v0 is a successor cardinal) iff (v0 is a cardinal number and for some v1, (v1 is a cardinal number and v0 is equal to \CARDsucc{ v1 })))

Theorem:
  for all v0, (if v0 is a cardinal number then for all v1, (if v1 is an element of \CARDsucc{ v0 } then \SETcard{ v1 } \ORDleq v0))
Proof:
Qed.

Definition:
  for all v0, ((v0 is equal to \Set) iff (v0 is a class and for all v1, (v1 is an element of v0 iff (v1 is a set and v1 is an object))))

Theorem (Cantor_Paradox_I):
  it is wrong that (\Card is a set)
Proof:
  \Card is a set
  \SETunionover \Card is a set
  for all v0, (if v0 is an ordinal number then v0 is an element of \SETunionover \Card)
  Proof:
    \alpha is an ordinal number
    \beta is an ordinal number and \beta is infinite and \alpha \ORDleq \beta
    \kappa is a cardinal number and \beta \ORDless \kappa
    \alpha is an element of \kappa and \kappa is an element of \Card
    \alpha is an element of \SETunionover \Card
  Qed.
  \Ord is a subclass of \SETunionover \Card
  \Ord is a set
  falsity holds
Qed.

Theorem (Cantor_Paradox_II):
  it is wrong that (\Set is a set)
Proof:
  it is wrong that (the thesis holds)
  \SETpow( \Set ) is a subset of \Set
  \SETcard{ \SETpow( \Set ) } \ORDleq \SETcard{ \Set }
  falsity holds
  Proof:
    for all v0, (if v0 is a set then \SETcard{ v0 } \ORDless \SETcard{ \SETpow( v0 ) })
  Qed.
Qed.

